    <header>
        <h1>Understanding Asynchronous Programming in Modern .NET</h1>

        <p>
            Modern .NET applications frequently perform operations that take time to
            complete, such as reading files, querying databases, calling web APIs,
            and communicating with external services.
        </p>

        <p>
            If these operations run synchronously, the application may become
            unresponsive while waiting for the work to finish.
            Asynchronous programming helps solve this problem by allowing other work
            to continue while an operation is in progress.
        </p>

        <p>
            In this guide, you'll learn the fundamentals of asynchronous programming
            in C#, how <code>async</code> and <code>await</code> work, and the best
            practices for building responsive and scalable .NET applications.
        </p>
    </header>
    <br />
    <section>
        <h2>What Is Asynchronous Programming?</h2>

        <p>
            Asynchronous programming is a technique that allows a program to start
            a task and continue doing other work while waiting for that task to
            complete.
        </p>

        <p>
            Instead of blocking the current thread, the application can remain
            responsive and handle additional operations efficiently.
        </p>

        <p>
            Common examples include:
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li>Calling a REST API.</li>
            <li>Reading large files.</li>
            <li>Saving data to a database.</li>
            <li>Downloading content from the internet.</li>
            <li>Processing background tasks.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Synchronous vs Asynchronous Execution</h2>

        <p>
            Consider a program that downloads data from a web service.
        </p>

        <h3>Synchronous Approach</h3>

        <pre><code>string data = DownloadData();

            Console.WriteLine(data);</code></pre>

            <p>
                The application must wait until the download finishes before continuing.
            </p>

            <h3>Asynchronous Approach</h3>

            <pre><code>string data = await DownloadDataAsync();

                Console.WriteLine(data);</code></pre>

                <p>
                    While waiting for the operation to complete, the application can perform
                    other work or remain responsive to user input.
                </p>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2>Understanding Tasks</h2>

                <p>
                    In modern .NET, asynchronous operations are commonly represented by the
                    <code>Task</code> class.
                </p>

                <pre><code>Task task = SomeOperationAsync();</code></pre>

                <p>
                    A Task represents work that may complete in the future.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Tasks are the foundation of asynchronous programming in C#.
                </p>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h2>Using async and await</h2>

                <p>
                    The <code>async</code> keyword marks a method as asynchronous, while
                    <code>await</code> pauses execution until the awaited task completes.
                </p>

                <pre><code>public async Task GetDataAsync()
                    {
                    await Task.Delay(2000);

                    Console.WriteLine("Operation completed.");
                    }</code></pre>

                    <p>
                        In this example, the method waits for two seconds without blocking
                        the calling thread.
                    </p>
                </section>

                <section>
                    <h2>A Simple Example</h2>

                    <pre><code>public async Task RunAsync()
                        {
                        Console.WriteLine("Starting...");

                        await Task.Delay(3000);

                        Console.WriteLine("Finished.");
                        }</code></pre>

                        <h3>Output</h3>

                        <pre><code>Starting...
                            Finished.</code></pre>

                            <p>
                                During the delay period, the application remains free to perform
                                additional work.
                            </p>
                        </section>

                        <section>
                            <h2>Returning Values from Async Methods</h2>

                            <p>
                                Asynchronous methods can return values using
                                <code>Task&lt;T&gt;</code>.
                            </p>

                            <pre><code>public async Task&lt;string&gt; GetMessageAsync()
                                {
                                await Task.Delay(1000);

                                return "Hello from .NET";
                                }</code></pre>

                                <p>
                                    Calling the method:
                                </p>

                                <pre><code>string message =
                                    await GetMessageAsync();

                                    Console.WriteLine(message);</code></pre>
                                </section>

                                <section>
                                    <h2>Running Multiple Tasks</h2>

                                    <p>
                                        Multiple asynchronous operations can run concurrently.
                                    </p>

                                    <pre><code>Task task1 = Task.Delay(1000);
                                        Task task2 = Task.Delay(2000);

                                        await Task.WhenAll(task1, task2);

                                        Console.WriteLine("All tasks completed.");</code></pre>

                                        <p>
                                            Task.WhenAll waits until all supplied tasks finish execution.
                                        </p>
                                    </section>

                                    <section>
                                        <h2>Why Asynchronous Programming Matters</h2>

                                        <ul>
                                            <li>Improves application responsiveness.</li>
                                            <li>Reduces thread blocking.</li>
                                            <li>Enhances scalability.</li>
                                            <li>Improves user experience.</li>
                                            <li>Supports modern cloud-based applications.</li>
                                        </ul>

                                        <p>
                                            Asynchronous programming is especially important for ASP.NET Core,
                                            APIs, desktop applications, and mobile apps.
                                        </p>
                                    </section>

                                    <section>
                                        <h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

                                        <h3>Blocking Async Code</h3>

                                        <pre><code>var result = GetDataAsync().Result;</code></pre>

                                        <p>
                                            Using Result or Wait() can lead to deadlocks and should generally
                                            be avoided.
                                        </p>

                                        <h3>Forgetting await</h3>

                                        <pre><code>GetDataAsync();</code></pre>

                                        <p>
                                            Without await, exceptions may go unnoticed and execution may continue
                                            before the task completes.
                                        </p>

                                        <h3>Using async void Unnecessarily</h3>

                                        <pre><code>public async void ProcessData()</code></pre>

                                        <p>
                                            Prefer Task-returning methods whenever possible.
                                        </p>
                                    </section>

                                    <section>
                                        <h2>Best Practices</h2>

                                        <ul>
                                            <li>Use async and await consistently.</li>
                                            <li>Prefer Task and Task&lt;T&gt; over async void.</li>
                                            <li>Avoid blocking asynchronous code.</li>
                                            <li>Use Task.WhenAll for independent operations.</li>
                                            <li>Handle exceptions properly.</li>
                                            <li>Keep asynchronous methods focused and readable.</li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </section>

                                    <section>
                                        <h2>Real-World Examples</h2>

                                        <ul>
                                            <li>Loading user data from a database.</li>
                                            <li>Downloading files.</li>
                                            <li>Calling external APIs.</li>
                                            <li>Reading large documents.</li>
                                            <li>Processing cloud storage operations.</li>
                                            <li>Sending emails in background services.</li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </section>
                                    <br />
                                    <section>
                                        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

                                        <h3>What is async in C#?</h3>

                                        <p>
                                            The async keyword allows a method to use await and perform
                                            asynchronous operations.
                                        </p>

                                        <h3>What does await do?</h3>

                                        <p>
                                            Await pauses execution until a task completes without blocking the
                                            current thread.
                                        </p>

                                        <h3>Is asynchronous programming faster?</h3>

                                        <p>
                                            It does not necessarily make operations faster, but it improves
                                            responsiveness and scalability.
                                        </p>

                                        <h3>Should all methods be async?</h3>

                                        <p>
                                            No. Only methods that perform asynchronous operations should be
                                            asynchronous.
                                        </p>
                                    </section>


